The Chronicle Midlands Bureau Chief
THREE armed robbers who allegedly got away with US$13 000 and three vehicles in three incidents in Mvuma and Mberengwa in less than 24 hours have been arrested in Masvingo. <img class="wp-image-624226 size-full" src="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2022/07/Untitled-26-1.jpg" alt="" width="680" height="380" srcset="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2022/07/Untitled-26-1.jpg 680w, https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2022/07/Untitled-26-1-360x200.jpg 360w" sizes="(max-width: 680px) 100vw, 680px" /> armed robbers Midlands provincial police spokesperson, Inspector Emmanuel Mahoko, confirmed the arrest of Rhinos Takawira (42) of Chivi, Tinashe Marimo (22) of Murehwa and Praise Gudlanga (30) of Mutare. He said police recovered two pistols, a safe, cellphones, three stolen motor vehicles and US$1 500. “A notorious armed robbery gang which came to fame after carjacking two motorists in Mvuma, in one night, have been accounted for in a smart arrest in Masvingo. “The robbers’ Mvuma exploits were reported in the media on June 30,” said Insp Mahoko. He said on June 28, Takawira, Marimo and Gudlanga allegedly robbed a Mvuma businessman of US$2 000 and a Honda Fit before robbing a woman of her Toyota double cab motor vehicle. <img class="wp-image-624232 size-full" src="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2022/07/Untitled-27-1.jpg" alt="" width="680" height="380" srcset="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2022/07/Untitled-27-1.jpg 680w, https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2022/07/Untitled-27-1-360x200.jpg 360w" sizes="(max-width: 680px) 100vw, 680px" /> Honda Fit After the Mvuma incidents, Insp Mahoko said the trio allegedly drove the vehicle to a fuel filling station in Mberengwa the following day. “They fired one shot from a pistol and robbed the filling station, getting away with a safe containing US$11 000 and a Toyota Wish motor vehicle. They left the twin cab stolen from Mvuma at the filling station,” he said. Insp Mahoko said on June 30 around 1PM, police officers in Masvingo saw the gang while it was in the process of abandoning the stolen Toyota Wish to board a Zupco bus. “All three were swiftly arrested and interviews that followed unravelled a plethora of robbery cases committed mostly in Masvingo and Midlands Province. The arrested suspects are assisting investigations while being held in police custody in Masvingo,” he said. Insp Mahoko said police are still to come up with the precise number of cases committed by the three and values involved. “Investigations are progressing.  As it stands police have recovered two pistols, a safe, cellphones, three stolen motor vehicles and US$1 500,” he said.